  <static seed="1577" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/RationalEquations/solveRationalEquations3.pg">
    <statement><p>Solve the equation.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ {\frac{r+3}{2r+3}} = \frac{4}{7} }</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="34" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left\{9\right\}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To get rid of all fractions in this equation, we multiple all terms with the common denominator. In this equation, the common denominator is <m>{7\mathopen{}\left(2r+3\right)}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   {\frac{r+3}{2r+3}} \amp = \frac{4}{7} \\
   {\frac{r+3}{2r+3}} \cdot {7\mathopen{}\left(2r+3\right)} \amp = \frac{4}{7} \cdot {7\mathopen{}\left(2r+3\right)} \\
   7(r+3) \amp = 4(2r+3) \\
   7r+21 \amp = 8r+12 \\
   7r+21  \mathbf{-8r-21} \amp = 8r+12 \mathbf{-8r-21}  \\
   -1r \amp = -9 \\
   \frac{-1r}{-1} \amp = \frac{-9}{-1} \\
   r \amp = 9
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>We must check solutions when we solve rational equations. By the original equation, the domain condition is <m>{7\mathopen{}\left(2r+3\right)} \ne 0</m>, or <m>r \ne -\frac{3}{2}</m>. This doesn<rsq/>t conflict with the solution above, so the solution is <m>r = 9</m>.</p>
</solution>
